<h1>Matrix Multiplication (DSA)</h1>

<p>Matrix multiplication is a fundamental operation in computer science and data structures (DSA) with broad applications in graphics, machine learning, and numerical simulations. In this process, two matrices are multiplied to produce a new matrix. Understanding matrix multiplication is crucial, especially when dealing with algorithms that require complex calculations, such as those used in dynamic programming and graph theory.</p>

<h2>Basics of Matrix Multiplication</h2>

<p>Matrix multiplication is only possible under specific conditions. Given two matrices, <strong>A</strong> and <strong>B</strong>:</p>

<ul>
    <li>Matrix <strong>A</strong> has dimensions <code>m × n</code>, meaning it has <strong>m</strong> rows and <strong>n</strong> columns.</li>
    <li>Matrix <strong>B</strong> has dimensions <code>n × p</code>, meaning it has <strong>n</strong> rows and <strong>p</strong> columns.</li>
</ul>

<p>To multiply these two matrices, the number of columns in <strong>A</strong> must equal the number of rows in <strong>B</strong>. The resulting matrix <strong>C</strong> will have dimensions <code>m × p</code>, where each element <code>C[i][j]</code> is computed as the dot product of the <strong>i</strong>-th row of <strong>A</strong> and the <strong>j</strong>-th column of <strong>B</strong>.</p>

<h2>Step-by-Step Process</h2>

<ol>
    <li><strong>Initialize Resultant Matrix:</strong>  
        The product of matrix <strong>A</strong> (<code>m × n</code>) and matrix <strong>B</strong> (<code>n × p</code>) yields a new matrix <strong>C</strong> with dimensions <code>m × p</code>.
    </li>
    <li><strong>Dot Product Calculation:</strong>  
        For each element of matrix <strong>C</strong>, denoted as <code>C[i][j]</code>, you calculate the sum of the products of corresponding elements from row <strong>i</strong> of matrix <strong>A</strong> and column <strong>j</strong> of matrix <strong>B</strong>. Formally, this can be expressed as:
        <pre><code>C[i][j] = ∑(A[i][k] * B[k][j]), for k = 1 to n</code></pre>
    </li>
</ol>

