    <li><code>C[1][1] = (3 × 6) + (4 × 8) = 18 + 32 = 50</code></li>
</ul>

<h2>Time Complexity</h2>

<p>Matrix multiplication has a time complexity of <code>O(m × n × p)</code>, where <strong>m</strong>, <strong>n</strong>, and <strong>p</strong> are the dimensions of matrices <strong>A</strong> (<code>m × n</code>) and <strong>B</strong> (<code>n × p</code>). This means that as the size of the matrices increases, the number of operations required for matrix multiplication increases exponentially.</p>

<h2>Strassen’s Algorithm</h2>

<p>In standard matrix multiplication, the computational complexity is <code>O(n³)</code>. However, Strassen’s algorithm offers an optimized approach with a complexity of approximately <code>O(n<sup>2.81</sup>)</code>. Strassen’s method divides each matrix into submatrices and reduces the number of multiplications needed, improving efficiency for large matrices.</p>

<h2>Applications</h2>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Graph Theory:</strong> Matrix multiplication is often used to solve problems related to graph traversal and finding shortest paths.</li>
    <li><strong>Dynamic Programming:</strong> Certain dynamic programming algorithms, such as those for solving matrix chain multiplication problems, utilize matrix multiplication.</li>
    <li><strong>Machine Learning:</strong> Many machine learning models, particularly neural networks, rely heavily on matrix operations for tasks like forward and backward propagation.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>

<p>Matrix multiplication is a foundational concept with broad applications in computer science. While the basic process involves taking the dot product of rows and columns from two matrices, optimizing this operation (e.g., using Strassen’s algorithm) is essential for handling large datasets efficiently.</p>

